9.3.2. Third panel: Religion and Gender
From Women’s Autonomy Over Health Care to Heredity and Beyond
Presentation B
Anne-Virginie Niny, Metaxas Center for the Social Sciences/EHESS/CNRS
Through a case study on South Indian women’s use of contraception based on in-depth ethnographic research in Tamil Nadu (South India), I argue that availability does not equate with appropriation of a technology. It is necessary to deconstruct to simplistic views according to which autonomous use of contraceptive technologies is synonymous with empowerment of women vis-à-vis men and the family. The issue is rather the culturally sensitive possibility of being in control and ‘alone’ when doing family planning. Autonomy can be best understood in terms of negotiation rather than in terms of isolation and disconnection.
